GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 992
Short Title: Timeshare Foreclosures. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Cairns, Tyson, Ross, and Winslow (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Finance, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 14, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO CREATE A TIMESHARE TRUSTEE FORECLOSURE PROCESS FOR
3 CERTAIN DELINQUENT ASSESSMENTS FOR TIMESHARES LOCATED IN THIS
4 STATE.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. G.S. 93A-62 reads as rewritten:
7 "§ 93A-62. Delinquent assessments; developer guarantee.
8 (a) Delinquent assessments may bear interest at the highest rate permitted by law or at
9 some lesser rate established by the managing entity. In addition to interest, the managing entity
10 may charge a reasonable administrative late fee for each delinquent assessment. Any costs of
11 collection, including reasonable collection agency fees and reasonable attorney's fees, incurred
12 in the collection of a delinquent assessment shall be paid by the owner and shall be secured by a
13 lien in favor of the managing entity upon the timeshare with respect to which the delinquent
14 assessment has been incurred.
15 (b) The managing entity may deny the use of the timeshare units or facilities, including
16 the denial of the right to make a reservation or the cancellation of a confirmed reservation for
17 timeshare periods, to any owner who is delinquent in the payment of any assessments made by
18 the managing entity against the owner for common expenses, in accordance with the following:
19 (1) The managing entity must, no less than 30 days after the date the assessment
20 is due, notify the owner in writing of the total amount of any delinquency
21 which then exists, including any accrued interest and late charges permitted
22 to be imposed under the terms of the timeshare program or by law and
23 including a per diem amount. The notice shall be sent to the owner at the
24 owner's known address as recorded in the books and records of the timeshare
25 program.
26 (2) The notice shall clearly state that the owner will not be permitted to use the
27 owner's timeshare, that the owner will not be permitted to make a reservation
28 in the timeshare program's reservation system, or that any confirmed
29 reservation may be canceled until the total amount of such delinquency is
30 satisfied in full or until the owner produces satisfactory evidence that the
31 delinquency does not exist.
32 (3) The notice shall be effective to bar the use of the owner and those claiming
33 use rights under the owner, including the owner's guests, lessees, and persons
34 receiving use rights in the timeshare through an exchange program; provided,
35 however, that (i) a managing entity desiring to deny the use of the timeshare
*H992-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 to persons receiving use rights in the delinquent owner's timeshare through an
2 exchange program that has an affiliation agreement with the managing entity
3 shall notify the affiliated exchange company in writing of the denial of use at
4 the time that the notice was sent to the owner and (ii) any person claiming
5 through the affiliated exchange program who has received a confirmed
6 assignment of the delinquent owner's use rights from the affiliated exchange
7 company prior to the expiration of 48 hours after the receipt by the affiliated
8 exchange company of the written notice from the managing entity shall be
9 permitted by the managing entity to use the owner's use rights.
10 (4) Any costs reasonably incurred by the managing entity in connection with its
11 compliance with the requirements of this section may be assessed by the
12 managing entity against the delinquent owner and collected in the same
13 manner as if those costs were common expenses of the timeshare program
14 allocable solely to the delinquent purchaser.
15 (5) A managing entity may not enforce the denial of use against any one owner
16 or group of owners without similarly enforcing it against all owners, including
17 all developers.
18 (c) In addition to the denial of use pursuant to subsection (b) of this section, the managing
19 entity may give further notice to the delinquent owner that the managing entity may rent the
20 delinquent owner's timeshare, or any use rights appurtenant thereto, in accordance with the
21 following:
22 (1) A further notice of intent to rent must be given no less than 30 days after the
23 date the assessment is due and must be delivered to the purchaser in the
24 manner required for notices under subsection (b) of this section.
25 (2) The notice shall state that unless the owner satisfies the delinquency in full, or
26 unless the owner produces satisfactory evidence that the delinquency does not
27 exist, the purchaser will be bound by the terms of any rental contract entered
28 into by the managing entity with respect to the owner's timeshare or
29 appurtenant use rights.
30 (3) The notice shall state that the owner will remain liable for any difference
31 between the amount of the delinquency and the net amount produced by the
32 rental contract and applied against the delinquency, and the managing entity
33 shall not be required to provide any further notice to the owner regarding any
34 residual delinquency.
35 (4) The managing entity's efforts to secure a rental shall not commence on a date
36 earlier than 10 days after the date of the notice of intent to rent.
37 (5) The managing entity must apply the proceeds of any rental, net of any rental
38 commissions, cleaning charges, travel agent commissions, or any other
39 commercially reasonable charges reasonably and usually incurred by the
40 managing entity in securing rentals to the delinquent owner's account.
41 (6) A managing entity may make a reasonable determination regarding the
42 priority of rentals of timeshares and, if the delinquent owner whose timeshare
43 is rented cannot be specifically determined due to the structure of the
44 timeshare program, the managing entity may allocate any net rental proceeds
45 in any reasonable manner.
46 (7) In securing a rental, the managing entity shall not be required to obtain the
47 highest nightly rental rate available, nor any particular rental rate, and the
48 managing entity shall not be required to rent the entire timeshare or
49 appurtenant rights; however, the managing entity must use reasonable efforts
50 to secure a rental that is commensurate with other rentals of similar timeshares
51 or use rights generally secured at that time.
