1 insufficient to offset the amounts secured by the lien, and any successor to the owner that acquires
2 title to a timeshare as a result of a timeshare trustee foreclosure under G.S. 93A-62.1 shall be
3 exempt from liability for all unpaid assessments attributable to the timeshare or chargeable to the
4 previous owner that came due prior to acquisition of title by the successor.
5 (f) If the developer agrees to guarantee the level of assessments for the timeshare
6 program for any period of time, the developer may be excused from the payment of the
7 developer's share of the assessments that otherwise would have been assessed against
8 developer-owned timeshares during the guarantee period, provided that the developer guarantees
9 that (i) during the guarantee period the assessments against owner timeshares will not increase
10 over the dollar amount stated in the adopted, good-faith budget of the timeshare program and (ii)
11 the developer will pay any amount by which all common expenses incurred during the guarantee
12 period exceed the total revenues of the timeshare program during the guarantee period."
13 SECTION 2. Article 4 of Chapter 93A of the General Statutes is amended by adding
14 a new section to read:
15 "§ 93A-62.1. Procedure for timeshare trustee foreclosure of assessment liens.
16 (a) This section is intended to provide, as an alternative to judicial foreclosure, a simple
17 and inexpensive method of enforcing payment of assessments, to the knowledge of all persons,
18 and recognize, in authorizing this timeshare trustee foreclosure proceeding, that all persons
19 owning a timeshare know or should know that the assessment lien on their timeshare may be
20 foreclosed and the timeshare sold for failure to pay assessments.
21 (b) A claim of lien complying with the requirements of G.S. 93A-62(d)(3) and subsection
22 (d) of this section must be filed in the office of the clerk of the superior court of the county in
23 which the timeshare is located in the manner provided in this section.
24 (c) No fewer than 15 days prior to filing the claim of lien, the managing entity or the
25 holder of the lien shall mail a statement of the assessment amount due by first-class mail to the
26 owner's address as recorded in the books and records of the timeshare program. If the record
27 owner is a corporation or limited liability company, the statement shall also be sent by first-class
28 mail to the mailing address of the registered agent for the corporation or limited liability
29 company. Notwithstanding any provision of this Chapter to the contrary, there shall be no
30 requirement that notice under this subsection be mailed to an owner's timeshare unit or otherwise
31 posted at the timeshare project. The managing entity or the holder of the lien shall make diligent
32 efforts to ensure that its records contain the unit owner's mailing address.
33 (d) In addition to the requirements of G.S. 93A-62, a claim of lien shall contain the
34 following statement in print that is in boldface, capital letters and no smaller than the largest print
35 used elsewhere in the document:
36 "THIS DOCUMENT CONSTITUTES A LIEN AGAINST YOUR TIMESHARE, AND IF
37 THE LIEN IS NOT PAID, THE ASSOCIATION MAY PROCEED WITH A TIMESHARE
38 TRUSTEE FORECLOSURE AGAINST YOUR TIMESHARE UNDER NORTH CAROLINA
39 LAW."
40 The person signing the claim of lien on behalf of the holder shall attach to and file with the
41 claim of lien a certificate, that has been signed and sworn to or affirmed before a notary public,
42 certifying that notice of the lien was sent to the record owner and those entitled to receive notice,
43 pursuant to both of the following methods: (i) by registered or certified mail, return receipt
44 requested, or by designated delivery service pursuant to 26 U.S.C. § 7502(f)(2) with a delivery
45 receipt requested and (ii) by mailing a copy of the lien by regular, first-class mail, postage prepaid
46 to the owner's known address as recorded in the books and records of the timeshare program. As
47 used in this section, "delivery receipt" includes an electronic or facsimile receipt.
48 (e) Except as provided in subsection (s) of this section, no sooner than two years since
49 the indebtedness described in the claim of lien became due and after filing the claim of lien, the
50 managing entity, holder of the lien, or designated trustee may foreclose the lien by filing a
51 certificate, that has been signed and sworn to or affirmed before a notary public, with the clerk
Page 4 House Bill 992-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 of the superior court, showing the following: (i) the record owner of the timeshare on which there
2 is a lien for unpaid assessments, together with the amount of assessments, including taxes,
3 penalties, interest, and costs that are covered by the lien, (ii) the year or years for which the
4 assessments are due, (iii) a description of the timeshare sufficient to permit its identification by
5 parol testimony, and (iv) the filing information for the claim of lien if previously filed with the
6 clerk of the superior court. The fees for docketing and indexing of the certificate assessed
7 pursuant to G.S. 7A-308(a)(11) are payable to the clerk of the superior court at the time the
8 assessments are collected or the timeshare is sold.
9 (f) The managing entity, holder of the lien, or designated trustee filing the certificate
10 provided for in subsection (e) of this section shall, at least 30 days prior to docketing the
11 judgment, send notice of the assessment lien foreclosure to the owner in the same manner as a
12 claim of lien under subsection (d) of this section to the owner at the owner's known address as
13 recorded in the books and records of the timeshare program and to all lienholders with liens that
14 have attached after the effective date of the timeshare claim of lien filed in accordance with
15 subsection (b) of this section. The notice required by this subsection shall (i) state that a judgment
16 will be docketed and the proposed date of the docketing, (ii) state that the judgment will authorize
17 a sale of the timeshare pursuant to a timeshare trustee foreclosure proceeding, (iii) provide a brief
18 description of the timeshare affected, (iv) include the filing information for the claim of lien if
19 previously filed with the clerk of the superior court, and (v) state that the lien may be satisfied
20 prior to judgment being entered. The notice shall also include an objection form that the owner
21 can use to object to use of the timeshare trustee foreclosure process within 30 days of receipt of
22 the notice by signing and returning the objection form to the managing entity, holder of the lien,
23 or designated trustee, and in such event the lien may thereafter only be foreclosed by filing a
24 judicial foreclosure action. The objection form described in this subsection shall identify the
25 owner, the timeshare interest, and the return address of the trustee and shall state: "The
26 undersigned owner exercises the owner's right to object to the use of the timeshare trustee
27 foreclosure procedure contained in G.S. 93A-62.1." The notice required by this subsection may
28 be combined with the notice of lien required to be given pursuant to subsection (d) of this section
29 and shall also contain a statement in substantially the following form:
30 "You may choose to sign and send to the trustee the enclosed objection form, exercising your
31 right to object to the use of the timeshare trustee foreclosure procedure. Upon the trustee's receipt
32 of your signed objection form, the foreclosure of the lien with respect to the default specified in
33 this notice shall be subject to the judicial foreclosure procedure only. If you do not object to the
34 use of the timeshare trustee foreclosure procedure, you will not be subject to a deficiency
35 judgment, even if the proceeds from the sale of your timeshare interest are insufficient to offset
36 the amounts secured by the lien."
37 (g) If, within 10 days following the mailing of the notice required by subsection (f) of
38 this section, a return receipt or delivery receipt has not been received by the managing entity,
39 holder of the lien, or designated trustee indicating receipt of the notice, then the managing entity,
40 holder of the lien, or designated trustee shall have a notice published in a newspaper of general
41 circulation in the county where the timeshare is located once a week for two consecutive weeks
42 directed to, and naming, all unnotified lienholders and the owner that a judgment will be docketed
43 against the owner.
44 (h) All costs of mailing and publication, plus a charge of two hundred fifty dollars
45 ($250.00) to defray administrative costs, shall be added to the amount of assessments that are a
46 lien on the timeshare and shall be paid by the owner to the managing entity or holder of the lien
47 at the time the assessments are collected or the timeshare is sold.
48 (i) Immediately upon the docketing and indexing of a certificate as provided in
49 subsection (e) of this section, the assessments, including taxes, penalties, interest, and costs,
50 constitute a valid judgment against the timeshare described in the judgment with the priority
51 provided for claims of lien in G.S. 93A-62(d)(2). The judgment, except as expressly provided in
House Bill 992-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 this section, has the same force and effect as a duly rendered judgment of the superior court
2 directing sale of the timeshare for the satisfaction of the assessment lien, and it shall bear interest
3 at an annual rate of eight percent (8%).
4 (j) At any time prior to the issuance a certificate of sale in accordance with subdivision
5 (8) of subsection (l) of this section, any person entitled to notice under this section may appear
6 before the clerk of superior court and move to set aside the judgment on the ground that the
7 assessment has been paid or that the assessment lien on which the judgment is based is invalid.
8 (k) Upon payment in full of any judgment docketed under this section, together with
9 interest and costs accrued to the date of payment, the managing entity, holder of the lien, or
10 designated trustee receiving payment shall certify the fact of the payment to the clerk of superior
11 court and cancel the judgment.
12 (l) At any time after 30 days and before one year from the indexing of the judgment as
13 provided in subsection (e) of this section, at the request of the managing entity or holder of the
14 lien, the timeshare shall be sold by a trustee in a public auction held in the county in which the
15 timeshare project is located on the date, location, and starting time designated in the notice of
16 sale sent in accordance with this subsection. The trustee's sale shall occur at a location consistent
17 with G.S. 45-21.4. The timeshare trustee foreclosure sale shall be conducted in accordance with
18 the following:
19 (1) The managing entity or the holder of the lien shall appoint a trustee, who shall
20 conduct the sale and act as the auctioneer. The appointment of the trustee shall
21 be included in the claim of lien or the certificate. The managing entity or the
22 holder of the lien, at its option, may from time to time remove a trustee
23 previously appointed and appoint a successor trustee by filing a substitution
24 of trustee with the clerk of superior court. Counsel for the managing entity or
25 for the holder of the lien may be appointed by the managing entity or by the
26 holder of the lien to serve as the trustee and may serve in that capacity as long
27 as the owner does not contest the obligation to pay the amount of any sums
28 due the managing entity or the holder of the lien, or the validity, enforcement,
29 or foreclosure of the claim of lien as provided in subsection (f) of this section.
30 A trustee appointed pursuant to this subsection shall have the same fiduciary
31 duties and obligations as a trustee in the foreclosure of a deed of trust and is a
32 neutral third party. While serving as trustee in the foreclosure proceeding, a
33 trustee may not advocate for the managing entity or the holder of the lien or
34 the owner of the timeshare subject to foreclosure. The trustee shall be entitled
35 to a commission for services rendered which shall include fees, costs, and
36 expenses reasonably incurred by the trustee in connection with the
37 foreclosure, whether or not a sale is held. The trustee's commission shall be
38 paid without regard to any limitations on compensation otherwise provided by
39 law, including, without limitation, the provisions of G.S. 45-21.15. The
40 trustee may use a third party to conduct the sale on behalf of the trustee and
41 the trustee is liable for the conduct of the sale and the actions of the third party
42 with respect to the conduct of the sale.
43 (2) At least 30 days prior to the day fixed for the execution sale, the trustee shall
44 send notice by registered or certified mail, return receipt requested, or by
45 designated delivery service pursuant to 26 U.S.C. § 7502(f)(2) with a delivery
46 receipt requested, to the owner at the owner's known address as recorded in
47 the books and records of the timeshare program, in lieu of personal service,
48 and to all lienholders that received notice under subsection (f) of this section.
49 If within 10 days following the mailing of the notice of the sale a return receipt
50 or delivery receipt has not been received by the trustee indicating receipt of
